    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4c.20.24-26_0001-3" />
                <fw type="curatorial">24</fw>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                <address><addrLine>Skyrim Farm, Route 6,</addrLine>
                <addrLine>Columbia, Mo.,</addrLine></address> <date>5-22-'56</date>
                    </dateline>
                
                <address>
                <addrLine>Dr. &amp; Mrs. Slade Kendrick,</addrLine>
                <addrLine>Ithaca, N. Y.</addrLine>
                </address>
                
                
                <salute>Dear Friends:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Well, I'm here again &#8212; with precious memories and a heartful of thankfulness. I have seldom been as happy outside my own home as I was in yours. Mona <note type="curatorial">(his wife)</note> has heard all about you, and she shares in my affectionate thoughts of you two dear people.</p>
                
                <p>Mona opened the surprise envelope, and it <hi rend="underline">was</hi> a surprise truly &#8212; quite pleasing in the worldly sense, of course, but appreciated more as a further expression of your kindness, Slade, for I know it was your doing. Many thanks!</p>
                <note type="curatorial">WESTERN HISTORICAL MANUSCRIPTS COLLECTION
                UNIVERSITY OF MISSOURI
                COLUMBIA, MO.</note>
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4c.20.24-26_0002"/>
                <fw type="curatorial">25</fw>
                <fw type="authorial">-2-</fw>
                
                <p>I was rather weary when I reached home Sunday evening. It's a long, long wait in St. Louis and the station seats <hi rend="underline">are</hi> hard. But I rested on Monday and was ready for my Tuesday classes. During my absence, Nita, Mona decorated half of the house at least &#8212; and <hi rend="underline">what</hi> a difference! I don't know how she did it all in so short a time. I mention this because you spoke of going after your home in the same way.</p>
               
                <p>I think often of Dr. Thompson, and I hope I may see him again in this world. Please tell our lexicographer friend that I am sorry I could have no good talk with him, for I <hi rend="underline">did</hi> feel something special about him too. They were all fine, the men I met.</p>
                <note type="curatorial">WESTERN HISTORICAL MANUSCRIPTS COLLECTION
                    UNIVERSITY OF MISSOURI
                    COLUMBIA, MO.</note>
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4c.20.24-26_0003"/>
                <fw type="curatorial">26</fw>
                <fw type="authorial">-3-</fw>
                
                <p>Do let me know about <hi rend="underline">the Book's</hi> adventures among publishers. How I <hi rend="underline">do</hi> want to see it in print. As I think of it, I have a <hi rend="underline">good feeling</hi> with no back thoughts. It is so reasonable, so well-ordered; and it places no burden upon normal credulity, arouses no antagonism. Also it <hi rend="underline">flows</hi> along with no shocks, and ends in a quiet <del/> beauty.</p>
                
                <p>Yesterday was a stifling hot day. Some youngsters fainted in crowded schoolrooms. Today is quite cool. What strange weather &#8212; upset just as man's world is! We need rain again.</p>
                <closer>
                <salute>Love to you, dear people.</salute>
                
                <signed>John N.</signed>
                </closer>
                <note type="curatorial">WESTERN HISTORICAL MANUSCRIPTS COLLECTION
                UNIVERSITY OF MISSOURI
                COLUMBIA, MO.</note>
            </div1>
